Definition 6.9. For any $\mathbb{E}$-extension $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$, define $\widetilde{\ell}(\delta)\in\widetilde{\mathbb{E}}(C,A)$ by the following. • Take a span of morphisms $(C\overset{w}{\longleftarrow}D\overset{d}{\longrightarrow}U_{A})$ from some $D\in\mathscr{C}$, which satisfy $w\in w\mathit{Fib}\quad\text{and}\quad w^{\ast}\delta=d^{\ast}\rho_{A}.$ Then, define as $\widetilde{\ell}(\delta)=\ell(d)\circ\ell(w)^{-1}.$
Definition 2.7. Let $A,C\in\mathscr{C}$ be any pair of objects. Sequences of morphisms in $\mathscr{C}$ $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C\ \ \text{and}\ \ A% \overset{x^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{y^{\prime}}{% \longrightarrow}C$ are said to be equivalent if there exists an isomorphism $b\in\mathscr{C}(B,B^{\prime})$ which makes the following diagram commutative. $\xy(-16,0)*+{A}="0";(3,0)*+{}="1";(0,8)*+{B}="2";(0,-8)*+{B^{\prime}}="4";(-3,% 0)*+{}="5";(16,0)*+{C}="6";{\ar^{x}"0";"2"};{\ar^{y}"2";"6"};{\ar_{x^{\prime}}% "0";"4"};{\ar_{y^{\prime}}"4";"6"};{\ar^{b}_{\cong}"2";"4"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"1"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"5";"6"};\endxy$ We denote the equivalence class of $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C$ by $[A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C]$.
Definition 7.1. An extriangulated category $(\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ is said to be Frobenius if it satisfies the following conditions. (1) $(\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ has enough injectives and enough projectives. (2) $\mathrm{Proj}(\mathscr{C})=\mathrm{Inj}(\mathscr{C})$.
Definition 2.10. Let $\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E}$ be as above. A realization of $\mathbb{E}$ is said to be additive, if it satisfies the following conditions. (i) For any $A,C\in\mathscr{C}$, the split $\mathbb{E}$-extension $0\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ satisfies $\mathfrak{s}(0)=0.$ (ii) For any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions $\delta=(A,\delta,C)$ and $\delta^{\prime}=(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$, $\mathfrak{s}(\delta\oplus\delta^{\prime})=\mathfrak{s}(\delta)\oplus\mathfrak{% s}(\delta^{\prime})$ holds.
Definition 2.3. Let $(A,\delta,C),(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$ be any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions. A morphism $(a,c)\colon(A,\delta,C)\to(A^{\prime},\delta^{\prime},C^{\prime})$ of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions is a pair of morphisms $a\in\mathscr{C}(A,A^{\prime})$ and $c\in\mathscr{C}(C,C^{\prime})$ in $\mathscr{C}$, satisfying the equality $a_{\ast}\delta=c^{\ast}\delta^{\prime}.$ Simply we denote it as $(a,c)\colon\delta\to\delta^{\prime}$. We obtain the category $\mathbb{E}\text{-}\mathrm{Ext}(\mathscr{C})$ of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions, with the composition and the identities naturally induced from those in $\mathscr{C}$.
Definition 2.8. $\ \ $ (1) For any $A,C\in\mathscr{C}$, we denote as $0=[A\overset{\begin{bmatrix}1\\ 0\end{bmatrix}}{\longrightarrow}A\oplus C\overset{[0\ 1]}{\longrightarrow}C].$ (2) For any $[A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C]$ and $[A^{\prime}\overset{x^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{y^{\prime}}% {\longrightarrow}C^{\prime}]$, we denote as $[A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C]\oplus[A^{\prime}% \overset{x^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{y^{\prime}}{% \longrightarrow}C^{\prime}]=[A\oplus A^{\prime}\overset{x\oplus x^{\prime}}{% \longrightarrow}B\oplus B^{\prime}\overset{y\oplus y^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow% }C\oplus C^{\prime}].$
Definition 2.17. Let $\mathcal{D}\subseteq\mathscr{C}$ be a full additive subcategory, closed under isomorphisms. We say $\mathcal{D}$ is extension-closed if it satisfies the following condition. • If a conflation $A\to B\to C$ satisfies $A,C\in\mathcal{D}$, then $B\in\mathcal{D}$.
Definition 3.23. An object $P\in\mathscr{C}$ is called projective if it satisfies the following condition. • For any $\mathbb{E}$-triangle $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{\delta}{\dashrightarrow}$ and any morphism $c\in\mathscr{C}(P,C)$, there exists $b\in\mathscr{C}(P,B)$ satisfying $y\circ b=c$. We denote the full subcategory of projective objects in $\mathscr{C}$ by $\mathrm{Proj}(\mathscr{C})$. Dually, the full subcategory of injective objects in $\mathscr{C}$ is denoted by $\mathrm{Inj}(\mathscr{C})$.
Definition 2.12. We call the pair $(\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ an external triangulation of $\mathscr{C}$ if it satisfies the following conditions. In this case, we call $\mathfrak{s}$ an $\mathbb{E}$-triangulation of $\mathscr{C}$, and call the triplet $(\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ an externally triangulated category, or for short, extriangulated category. (ET1) $\mathbb{E}\colon\mathscr{C}^{\mathrm{op}}\times\mathscr{C}\to\mathit{Ab}$ is a biadditive functor. (ET2) $\mathfrak{s}$ is an additive realization of $\mathbb{E}$. (ET3) Let $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})$ be any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions, realized as $\mathfrak{s}(\delta)=[A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{% \longrightarrow}C],\ \ \mathfrak{s}(\delta^{\prime})=[A^{\prime}\overset{x^{% \prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{y^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}C^{% \prime}].$ For any commutative square $\xy(-12,6)*+{A}="0";(0,6)*+{B}="2";(12,6)*+{C}="4";(-12,-6)*+{A^{\prime}}="10"% ;(0,-6)*+{B^{\prime}}="12";(12,-6)*+{C^{\prime}}="14";{\ar^{x}"0";"2"};{\ar^{y% }"2";"4"};{\ar_{a}"0";"10"};{\ar^{b}"2";"12"};{\ar_{x^{\prime}}"10";"12"};{\ar% _{y^{\prime}}"12";"14"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"12"};\endxy$ in $\mathscr{C}$, there exists a morphism $(a,c)\colon\delta\to\delta^{\prime}$ which is realized by $(a,b,c)$. (ET3)${}^{\mathrm{op}}$ Let $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ and $\delta^{\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(C^{\prime},A^{\prime})$ be any pair of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions, realized by $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C\ \ \text{and}\ \ A% ^{\prime}\overset{x^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}B^{\prime}\overset{y^{\prime}}{% \longrightarrow}C^{\prime}$ respectively. For any commutative square $\xy(-12,6)*+{A}="0";(0,6)*+{B}="2";(12,6)*+{C}="4";(-12,-6)*+{A^{\prime}}="10"% ;(0,-6)*+{B^{\prime}}="12";(12,-6)*+{C^{\prime}}="14";{\ar^{x}"0";"2"};{\ar^{y% }"2";"4"};{\ar_{b}"2";"12"};{\ar^{c}"4";"14"};{\ar_{x^{\prime}}"10";"12"};{\ar% _{y^{\prime}}"12";"14"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"2";"14"};\endxy$ in $\mathscr{C}$, there exists a morphism $(a,c)\colon\delta\to\delta^{\prime}$ which is realized by $(a,b,c)$. (ET4) Let $(A,\delta,D)$ and $(B,\delta^{\prime},F)$ be $\mathbb{E}$-extensions realized by $A\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{f^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}D\ \ \text{% and}\ \ B\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{g^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}F$ respectively. Then there exist an object $E\in\mathscr{C}$, a commutative diagram $\xy(-21,7)*+{A}="0";(-7,7)*+{B}="2";(7,7)*+{D}="4";(-21,-7)*+{A}="10";(-7,-7)*% +{C}="12";(7,-7)*+{E}="14";(-7,-21)*+{F}="22";(7,-21)*+{F}="24";{\ar^{f}"0";"2% "};{\ar^{f^{\prime}}"2";"4"};{\ar@{=}"0";"10"};{\ar_{g}"2";"12"};{\ar^{d}"4";"% 14"};{\ar_{h}"10";"12"};{\ar_{h^{\prime}}"12";"14"};{\ar_{g^{\prime}}"12";"22"% };{\ar^{e}"14";"24"};{\ar@{=}"22";"24"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"12"};{% \ar@{}|\circlearrowright"2";"14"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"12";"24"};\endxy$ in $\mathscr{C}$, and an $\mathbb{E}$-extension $\delta^{\prime\prime}\in\mathbb{E}(E,A)$ realized by $A\overset{h}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{h^{\prime}}{\longrightarrow}E$, which satisfy the following compatibilities. (i) $D\overset{d}{\longrightarrow}E\overset{e}{\longrightarrow}F$ realizes $\mathbb{E}(F,f^{\prime})(\delta^{\prime})$, (ii) $\mathbb{E}(d,A)(\delta^{\prime\prime})=\delta$, (iii) $\mathbb{E}(E,f)(\delta^{\prime\prime})=\mathbb{E}(e,B)(\delta^{\prime})$. By (iii), $(f,e)\colon\delta^{\prime\prime}\to\delta^{\prime}$ is a morphism of $\mathbb{E}$-extensions, realized by $(f,\mathrm{id}_{C},e)\colon[A\overset{h}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{h^{\prime}}% {\longrightarrow}E]\to[B\overset{g}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{g^{\prime}}{% \longrightarrow}F].$ (ET4)${}^{\mathrm{op}}$ Dual of (ET4) (see Remark 2.22).
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y}\subseteq\mathscr{C}$ be any pair of full subcategories closed under isomorphisms. Define full subcategories $\mathrm{Cone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$ and $\mathrm{CoCone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$ of $\mathscr{C}$ as follows. These are closed under isomorphisms. (i) $C\in\mathscr{C}$ belongs to $\mathrm{Cone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$ if and only if it admits a conflation $X\to Y\to C$ satisfying $X\in\mathcal{X},Y\in\mathcal{Y}$. (ii) $C\in\mathscr{C}$ belongs to $\mathrm{CoCone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$ if and only if it admits a conflation $C\to X\to Y$ satisfying $X\in\mathcal{X},Y\in\mathcal{Y}$. If $\mathcal{X}$ and $\mathcal{Y}$ are additive subcategories of $\mathscr{C}$, then so are $\mathrm{Cone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$ and $\mathrm{CoCone}(\mathcal{X},\mathcal{Y})$, by condition (ET2).
Definition 6.15. For an $\mathbb{E}$-triangle $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{\delta}{\dashrightarrow}$, its associated standard triangle in $\widetilde{\mathscr{C}}$ is defined to be $A\overset{\ell(x)}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{\ell(y)}{\longrightarrow}C% \overset{\widetilde{\ell}(\delta)}{\longrightarrow}A[1].$ A distinguished triangle in $\widetilde{\mathscr{C}}$ is a triangle isomorphic to some standard triangle.
Definition 5.5. $\mathcal{M}$ is called an admissible model structure if it satisfies the following conditions for any morphism $f\in\mathscr{C}(A,B)$. (1) $f\in w\mathit{Cof}$ if and only if it is an inflation with $\mathrm{Cone}(f)\in\mathcal{S}$. (2) $f\in\mathit{Fib}$ if and only if it is a deflation with $\mathrm{CoCone}(f)\in\mathcal{T}$. (3) $f\in\mathit{Cof}$ if and only if it is an inflation with $\mathrm{Cone}(f)\in\mathcal{U}$. (4) $f\in w\mathit{Fib}$ if and only if it is a deflation with $\mathrm{CoCone}(f)\in\mathcal{V}$.
Definition 3.1. Assume $\mathscr{C}$ and $\mathbb{E}$ satisfy (ET1). By Yoneda’s lemma, any $\mathbb{E}$-extension $\delta\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ induces natural transformations $\delta_{\sharp}\colon\mathscr{C}(-,C)\Rightarrow\mathbb{E}(-,A)\ \ \text{and}% \ \ \delta^{\sharp}\colon\mathscr{C}(A,-)\Rightarrow\mathbb{E}(C,-).$ For any $X\in\mathscr{C}$, these $(\delta_{\sharp})_{X}$ and $\delta^{\sharp}_{X}$ are given as follows. (1) $(\delta_{\sharp})_{X}\colon\mathscr{C}(X,C)\to\mathbb{E}(X,A)\ ;\ f\mapsto f^{% \ast}\delta$. (2) $\delta^{\sharp}_{X}\colon\mathscr{C}(A,X)\to\mathbb{E}(C,X)\ ;\ g\mapsto g_{% \ast}\delta$. We abbreviately denote $(\delta_{\sharp})_{X}(f)$ and $\delta^{\sharp}_{X}(g)$ by $\delta_{\sharp}f$ and $\delta^{\sharp}g$, when there is no confusion.
Definition 4.12. Let $(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T})$ and $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ be cotorsion pairs on $\mathscr{C}$. Then the pair $\mathcal{P}=((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ is called a twin cotorsion pair if it satisfies $\mathbb{E}(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{V})=0$. (Pairs of cotorsion pairs are considered in abelian/exact categories in [Ho1, Ho2], and in triangulated categories in [Na2, Na3].) If moreover it satisfies $\mathcal{S}\cap\mathcal{T}=\mathcal{U}\cap\mathcal{V}(=\mathcal{I})$, then $\mathcal{P}$ is called a concentric twin cotorsion pair similarly as in the triangulated case [Na4]. In this case, we put $\mathcal{Z}=\mathcal{T}\cap\mathcal{U}$.
Definition 7.13. Let $\mathcal{P}=((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ be a Hovey twin cotorsion pair on $\mathscr{C}$. We define mutation with respect to $(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{V})$ as a $\mathbb{Z}$-action on $\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}$ given by $\mu_{n}=\mathbb{I}\circ[n]\circ\mathbb{R}$, i.e., $\mu_{n}\colon\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}\to\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}\ ;\ (% \mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})\mapsto\big{(}\mathcal{U}\cap\ell^{-1}(\ell(\mathcal{A% })[n]),\mathcal{T}\cap\ell^{-1}(\ell(\mathcal{B})[n])\big{)}$ for any $n\in\mathbb{Z}$.
Definition 6.7. By using $\mathbb{E}$-triangles $T^{C}\overset{t^{C}}{\longrightarrow}S^{C}\overset{s^{C}}{\longrightarrow}C% \overset{\lambda^{C}}{\dashrightarrow}$ one can define dually a functor $[-1]\colon\mathscr{C}\to\widetilde{\mathscr{C}}$ with $C[-1]=T^{C}$, which induces an endofunctor $[-1]$ of $\widetilde{\mathscr{C}}$.
Definition 2.5. For any $A,C\in\mathscr{C}$, the zero element $0\in\mathbb{E}(C,A)$ is called the split $\mathbb{E}$-extension.
Definition 5.11. Define classes of morphisms $\mathit{Fib},w\mathit{Fib},\mathit{Cof},w\mathit{Cof}$ and $\mathbb{W}$ in $\mathscr{C}$ as follows. (1) $f\in\mathit{Fib}$ if it is a deflation with $\mathrm{CoCone}(f)\in\mathcal{T}$. (2) $f\in w\mathit{Fib}$ if it is a deflation with $\mathrm{CoCone}(f)\in\mathcal{V}$. (3) $f\in\mathit{Cof}$ if it is a inflation with $\mathrm{Cone}(f)\in\mathcal{U}$. (4) $f\in w\mathit{Cof}$ if it is a inflation with $\mathrm{Cone}(f)\in\mathcal{S}$. (5) $\mathbb{W}=w\mathit{Fib}\circ w\mathit{Cof}$.
Definition 3.9. Assume $(\mathscr{C},\mathbb{E},\mathfrak{s})$ satisfies (ET1),(ET2),(ET3),(ET3)${}^{\mathrm{op}}$. (1) For an inflation $f\in\mathscr{C}(A,B)$, take a conflation $A\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}B\to C$, and denote this $C$ by $\mathrm{Cone}(f)$. (2) For a deflation $f\in\mathscr{C}(A,B)$, take a conflation $K\to A\overset{f}{\longrightarrow}B$. We denote this $K$ by $\mathrm{CoCone}(f)$.
Definition 4.8. For a cotorsion pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ on $\mathscr{C}$, put $\mathcal{I}=\mathcal{U}\cap\mathcal{V}$, and call it the core of $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$. For any full additive subcategory $\mathcal{X}\subseteq\mathscr{C}$ containing $\mathcal{I}$, let $\mathcal{X}/\mathcal{I}$ denote the ideal quotient. The image of a morphism $f$ in the ideal quotient is denoted by $\underline{f}$.
Definition 6.21. For any $\mathbb{E}$-triangle $A\overset{x}{\longrightarrow}B\overset{y}{\longrightarrow}C\overset{\delta}{\dashrightarrow}$, take a cospan of morphisms $(T^{C}\overset{m}{\longrightarrow}E\overset{n}{\longleftarrow}A)$ to some $T\in\mathscr{C}$ satisfying $n\in w\mathit{Cof}\quad\text{and}\quad n_{\ast}\delta=m_{\ast}\lambda^{C}.$ Then, $\ell^{{\dagger}}(\delta)=\ell(n)^{-1}\circ\ell(m)\in\widetilde{\mathscr{C}}(C[% -1],A)$ is well-defined.
Definition 1. A closure operator on a functor $F:\mathscr{B}\rightarrow\mathscr{C}$ is an endofunctor $C:\mathscr{B}\rightarrow\mathscr{B}$ of $\mathscr{B}$ together with a natural transformation $c:1_{\mathscr{B}}\rightarrow C$ such that $FC=F\text{ and }F\cdot c=1_{F}.$ A closure operator will be written as an ordered pair $(C,c)$ of the data above.
Definition 6.1. We say that $\nu\in\mathfrak{h}^{*}$ is almost real (with respect to $q$) if $({\rm Im}(\nu),\alpha)<2\pi\log(q)^{-1}$ for all $\alpha\in\Delta$.
Definition 2.1. A multiplier on a rigid $C^{\ast}$-tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is a family of linear maps $\theta_{\alpha,\beta}:\operatorname{End}(\alpha\otimes\beta)\to\operatorname{% End}(\alpha\otimes\beta)$ indexed by $\alpha,\beta\in\mathcal{C}$ such that $\displaystyle\theta_{\alpha_{2},\beta_{2}}(UXV^{\ast})$ $\displaystyle=U\theta_{\alpha_{1},\beta_{1}}(X)V^{\ast},$ $\displaystyle\theta_{\alpha_{1}\otimes\alpha_{2},\beta_{1}\otimes\beta_{2}}(1% \otimes X\otimes 1)$ $\displaystyle=1\otimes\theta_{\alpha_{2},\beta_{1}}(X)\otimes 1$ for all $\alpha_{i},\beta_{i}\in\mathcal{C},X\in\operatorname{End}(\alpha_{2}\otimes% \beta_{1})$ and $U,V\in\mathrm{Mor}(\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2})\otimes\mathrm{Mor}(\beta_{2},\beta_{% 1})$.
Definition 3.1. The Fourier-Stieljes algebra $B(\mathcal{C})$ of a rigid $C^{\ast}$-tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is the algebra of functions $\varphi:\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})\to\mathcal{C}$ of the form $\varphi(\alpha)=d(\alpha)^{-1}\langle\Theta(\alpha)\xi,\eta\rangle\ \ \ (% \alpha\in\operatorname{Irr}(\mathcal{C})),$ where $\Theta:\mathbb{C}[\mathcal{C}]\to B(\mathcal{K})$ is an admissible representation of the fusion algebra and $\xi,\eta\in\mathcal{K}$. We call such a function $\varphi$ a (matrix) coefficient of $\Theta$. The algebra structure is given by pointwise multiplication.
Definition 5.1. A rigid $C^{\ast}$-tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is said to have the Howe-Moore property if for every positive definite function $\omega:{\rm{Irr}}({\mathcal{C}})\to\mathbb{C}$, we have $\omega\in c_{0}(\mathrm{Irr}(\mathcal{C}))\oplus\mathbb{C}$.
Definition 7.5. Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a compact quantum group. The discrete dual $\hat{\mathbb{G}}$ has property (T) if one (and hence all) of the following equivalent conditions is satisfied. (i) If a net of states $(\omega_{\lambda})_{\lambda}$ in $C_{u}(\mathbb{G})^{*}$ converges to $\varepsilon$ pointwise, then it converges in norm. (ii) There exists a projection $p\in C_{u}(\mathbb{G})$ such that $xp=\varepsilon(x)p$ for all $x\in C_{u}(\mathbb{G})$.
Definition 3.5. The Fourier algebra $A(\mathcal{C})$ of a rigid $C^{\ast}$-tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is defined as the predual of the von Neumann algebra $\lambda(\mathbb{C}[\mathcal{C}])^{\prime\prime}$.
Definition 7.1. A rigid $C^{\ast}$-tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ has property (T) if one (and hence all) of the following equivalent conditions is satisfied. (i) Every net $(\varphi_{\lambda})_{\lambda}$ of cp-multipliers $\varphi_{\lambda}:\operatorname{Irr}\mathcal{C}\to\mathbb{C}$ converging to $\varphi_{\varepsilon}$ pointwisely converges uniformly, i.e. $\sup_{x\in\operatorname{Irr}\mathcal{C}}|\varphi_{\lambda}(x)-1|\to 0$. (ii) If $(\omega_{\lambda})$ is a net of states on $C_{u}(\mathcal{C})$ converging to $\varepsilon$ in the weak*-topology, it must already converge in norm. (iii) There exists a unique nonzero projection $p\in C_{u}(\mathcal{C})$ such that $\alpha p=d(\alpha)p$ for all $\alpha\in\mathcal{C}$. Such a projection is the analogue of a Kazhdan projection in the setting of groups.
Definition 2.2 ([45], [38]). A generalized SE-correspondence of $\mathcal{C}$ is an $S$-bimodule $\mathcal{H}$ that, as a $T$-bimodule, decomposes into a direct sum of $T$-bimodules of the form $\mathcal{H}_{\alpha}\otimes\overline{\mathcal{H}_{\beta}}$, where $\alpha,\beta\in\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 7.7. A finite von Neumann algebra $(M,\tau)$ has property (T) if one (and hence all) of the following equivalent conditions is satisfied. (i) If $(\Phi_{\lambda}:M\to M)$ is a net of unital completely positive maps $\tau$-preserving maps converging to the identity pointwise on $L^{2}(M)$, i.e. $\|\Phi_{\lambda}(x)-x\|_{2}\to 0,\ \lambda\to\infty$ for all $x\in M$, then it already converges in norm, i.e. $\sup_{x\in M_{1}}\|\Phi_{\lambda}(x)-x\|_{2}\to 0\quad\textrm{as}\quad\lambda% \to\infty.$ (ii) For any $M$-$M$-bimodule $\mathcal{H}$ and any net $(\xi_{\lambda})$ of unit vectors satisfying $\langle x\xi_{\lambda}y,\xi_{\lambda}\rangle_{\mathcal{H}}\to\tau(xy)\quad% \text{as}\quad\lambda\to\infty$ for all $x,y\in M$ and $\tau(x)=\langle x\xi_{\lambda},\xi_{\lambda}\rangle=\langle\xi_{\lambda}x,\xi_% {\lambda}\rangle$ for all $\lambda$, there exists a net of $M$-central vectors $(\mu_{\lambda})$ with $\|\xi_{\lambda}-\mu_{\lambda}\|\to 0\quad\textrm{as}\quad\lambda\to\infty.$
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathbb{G}$ be a compact quantum group. The discrete quantum group $\widehat{\mathbb{G}}$ is said to have the central Howe-Moore property if $\lambda(\omega)\in c_{0}(\widehat{\mathbb{G}})\oplus\mathbb{C}$ for every central state $\omega$ on $C(\mathbb{G})$.
Definition 2.2. A braided finite tensor category satisfying the equivalent conditions 1–4 above is called factorisable.
Definition 3.4. Let $P$ be a poset and $Q$ an induced subposet of $P$. Define the induced subposet ${\rm Def}(P,Q)$ of ${\rm Poset}(P,P)$ whose underlying set consists of the order-preserving maps which fix each point of $Q$. The induced poset $Q$ is a strong deformation retract of $P$ if there is an element $f$ belonging to the identity component of ${\rm Def}(P,Q)$ with image contained in $Q$.
Definition 3.16. Let $\mathsf{K}$ be a finite simplicial complex and $\mathsf{L}$ a subcomplex of $\mathsf{K}$. The neighborhood of $\mathsf{L}$ in $\mathsf{K}$ is the subcomplex $\nu_{\mathsf{K}}(\mathsf{L})=\nu(\mathsf{L})=\bigcup_{v\in V(\mathsf{L})}{\rm st% }_{\mathsf{K}}(v)\subset\mathsf{K}.$ For a positive integer $r$, define the $r$-neighborhood $\nu^{r}(\mathsf{L})$ inductively by $\nu^{1}(\mathsf{L})=\nu(\mathsf{L})$, and $\nu^{s+1}(\mathsf{L})=\nu(\nu^{s}(\mathsf{L}))$. A pair of simplicial complexes $(\mathsf{K},\mathsf{L})$ is an $r$-NDR pair if there exists a subcomplex $\mathsf{A}$ of $\mathsf{K}$ containing $\nu^{r}(\mathsf{L})$ such that $\mathsf{L}$ is a strong deformation retract of $\mathsf{A}$.
Definition 4.7. Let $G$ be a graph and $H$ a subgraph of $G$. Define the neighborhood $\nu_{G}(H)=\nu(H)$ of $H$ in $G$ to be the subgraph of $H$ whose vertex set is $V(\nu(H))=\{v\in V(G)\;|\;\textrm{There is $w\in V(H)$ such that $(v,w)\in E(G% )$.}\}$ and whose edge set is $E(\nu(H))=\{(v,w)\in E(G)\;|\;\textrm{One of $v$ and $w$ is a vertex of $H$.}\}.$ For $r\geq 1$, define the $r$-neighborhood $\nu^{r}_{G}(H)=\nu^{r}(H)$ of $H$ inductively by $\nu^{1}(H)=\nu(H)$ and $\nu^{s+1}(H)=\nu(\nu^{s}(H))$.
Definition 3.6. Let $\mathsf{K}$ be a simplicial complex and $\mathsf{L}$ an induced subcomplex of $\mathsf{K}$. Define the induced subposet ${\rm Def}(\mathsf{K},\mathsf{L})$ of ${\rm Map}(\mathsf{K},\mathsf{K})$ whose underlying set consists of the simplicial multi-maps $\eta$ such that $\eta(v)=\{v\}$ for every $v\in V(\mathsf{L})$. The induced subcomplex $\mathsf{L}$ is a strong deformation retract of $\mathsf{K}$ if there is a simplicial map $f$ belonging to the identity component of ${\rm Def}(\mathsf{K},\mathsf{L})$ with image contained in $\mathsf{L}$.
Definition 3.3 ([Far87], Definition 1.1). A class $\mathcal{O}$ of objects of $\mathcal{M}$ is called locally small if for every object $M\in\mathcal{M}$ there exists a set of objects $\mathcal{O}^{\prime}\subseteq\mathcal{O}$ such that every morphism from an object in $\mathcal{O}$ to $M$ factors through an object in $\mathcal{O}^{\prime}$.
Definition 3.1 ([Tho80], Definition 4.1). Let $i:A\to B$ be a monomorphism in $\mathbf{Cat}$. We say $i$ is a sieve if for every $a\in\mathrm{ob}(A)$ and morphism $f:b\to i(a)$ in $B$, there exists morphism $f^{\prime}:b^{\prime}\to a$ in $A$ such that $i(f^{\prime})=f$. We say $i$ is a cosieve if for every $a\in\mathrm{ob}(A)$ and morphism $g:i(a)\to b$ in $B$, there exists morphism $f^{\prime}:a\to b^{\prime}$ in $A$ such that $i(f^{\prime})=f$. We say $i$ is a Dwyer map if it is a sieve and factorizes as $A\xrightarrow{f}W\xrightarrow{j}B$ such that $f$ is a monomorphism, $j:W\to B$ is a cosieve and there is a right adjoint $r:W\to A$ to $f$.
Definition 3.7. A functor $\mathcal{M}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathbf{sSet}$ is small if it is the left Kan extension of a functor $\mathcal{J}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathbf{sSet}$, where $\mathcal{J}$ is a small full subcategory of $\mathcal{M}$. We denote by $\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{M})$ the category of small functors from $\mathcal{M}^{\mathrm{op}}\to\mathbf{sSet}$.
Definition 3.5 ([DK84], [Far87]). A locally small class $\mathcal{O}$ of objects in $\mathcal{M}$ is called a collection of orbits, if the following axioms hold. Q1. Let $\xymatrix{O\otimes K\ar[r]\ar[d]&X_{a}\ar[d]\\ O\otimes L\ar[r]&X_{a+1}\\ }$ be a pushout in $\mathcal{M}$ where $O\in\mathcal{O}$ and $K\to L\in\mathcal{I}_{\mathbf{sSet}}$. Then for $O^{\prime}\in\mathcal{O}$, the diagram $\xymatrix{\mathrm{Hom}(O^{\prime},O\otimes K)\ar[r]\ar[d]&\mathrm{Hom}(O^{% \prime},X_{a})\ar[d]\\ \mathrm{Hom}(O^{\prime},O\otimes L)\ar[r]&\mathrm{Hom}(O^{\prime},X_{a+1})\\ }$ is a homotopy pushout in $\mathbf{sSet}$. Q2. Let $O\in\mathcal{O}$ and $X_{0}\to\cdots\to X_{a}\to X_{a+1}\to\cdots$ be a continuous transfinite sequence in $\mathcal{M}$ where each map $X_{a}\to X_{a+1}$ is as in Q1. Then the natural map $\mathrm{colim}_{a}\mathrm{Hom}(O,X_{a})\to\mathrm{Hom}(O,\mathrm{colim}_{a}X_{% a})$ is a weak equivalence in $\mathbf{sSet}$. Q3. There exists a limit ordinal $c$ such that if the sequence in Q2 is indexed by ordinals $<c$, then the natural map is an isomorphism.
Definition 3.2. We say $\mathcal{M}$ admits the $\mathcal{O}$-equivariant model structure if there is a model structure on $\mathcal{M}$ such that a morphism $X\to Y$ in $\mathcal{M}$ is a weak equivalence (resp. fibration) if and only if for every $O\in\mathcal{O}$, the induced map $\mathrm{Hom}(O,X)\to\mathrm{Hom}(O,Y)$ is a weak equivalence (resp. fibration) in $\mathbf{sSet}$ with the standard model structure.
Definition 3.1. A log-modular tensor category $\mathcal{C}$ is a finite tensor category which is ribbon, whose double is isomorphic to the Deligne product $\mathcal{C}\otimes\mathcal{C}^{opp}$.
Definition 2.3. Given two functors $\mathcal{D}$ and $\mathcal{C}$ from a category $A$ to an allegory $B$, a weak natural transformation is the data, for any object $M$ in the categry $A$, of a morphism ${F}_M\in\operatorname{Hom}(\mathcal{D}_M,\mathcal{C}_M)$, and such that for any object $M$ and $N$ in the category $A$, and any morphism $a\in\operatorname{Hom}(M,N)$ we have ${F}_N\circ\mathcal{D}(a)\subset\mathcal{C}(a)\circ{F}_M.$
