Definition 5.3. Whenever $(i^{\prime},i)\in F$, we define the $(i^{\prime},i)$-component of $f$ by $f_{i^{\prime}i}:=\phi_{i^{\prime}}\circ f\circ\phi_{i}^{-1}:V_{i}\to V_{i^{% \prime}}.$
Definition B.1. A natural relation between $G$ and $G^{\prime}$ is given by a pair $(F,K)$ of binary relations on objects, and a binary relation $R$ on morphisms $(F,K)\in{\mathcal{P}}(G_{0}^{\prime}\times G_{0})^{2},\qquad R\in{\mathcal{P}}% (G_{1}^{\prime}\times G_{1})$ such that: (NR) if $(g,h)\in R$, then letting $x:=\pi_{0}(g)$, $x^{\prime}:=\pi_{0}(g^{\prime})$, $y:=\pi_{1}(g)$, $y^{\prime}:=\pi_{1}(h)$, we have $(x,x^{\prime})\in F$ and $(y,y^{\prime})\in K$: $\xymatrix{x\ar@{-}[rd]^{F}\ar[rr]^{g}&&y\ar@{-}[rd]^{K}&\\ &x^{\prime}\ar[rr]^{h}&&y^{\prime}}$ If, moreover, $F=K$, we speak of a special natural relation.
Definition 3.1. We call atlas data (with model space $V$ and chart index $I$) the following: the index set $I$ is an e-pos $(I,E,L)$, and (1) to each $i\in I$, is associated a set $V_{i}\subset V$ (“chart range”), (2) to each pair $(i,j)\in E$ is associated a bijection $\phi_{ij}:V_{j}\to V_{i}$ such that $\qquad\qquad\phi_{ii}=\mathrm{id}_{V_{i}}$, $\qquad\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{jk}=\phi_{ik}$, $\qquad\phi_{ij}^{-1}=\phi_{ji}$, (3) if $i^{\prime}\leq i$, then $V_{i^{\prime}}\subset V_{i}$, and if $(i,j)\in E,(i^{\prime},j^{\prime})\in E,i^{\prime}\leq i,j^{\prime}\leq j$, then $\forall x\in V_{j^{\prime}}:\quad\phi_{i^{\prime}j^{\prime}}(x)=\phi_{ij}(x)\,.$ (4) if $i\leq m$ and $j\leq m$ and $(V_{i}\cap V_{j})\not=\emptyset$, then there exists a unique $k\in I$ with $k\leq i$ and $k\leq j$ and $V_{k}=V_{i}\cap V_{j}$. We write $[i,j]:=k$. We say that atlas data are topological if $V$ carries a topology, all $V_{i}$ are open and all $\phi_{ij}$ are homeomorphisms.
Definition 6.3. Morphism data, and morphisms, are said to have some property, such as smoothness, if all components $f_{ij}$ have this property.
Definition 2.4. If $(i,j)\in E$, we define the transition map $\phi_{ij}:=\phi_{i}\circ\phi_{j}^{-1}:V_{j}\to V_{i}$.
